Text.SourceString: You’re…the new farmer?//Tch. I see. No offense, but you look like you’ve never held a tool in your life.
I don’t know why <NPCName>Connor</> lets anyone move in. Our community is great just as it is.
I used to fish for a living, but I passed the torch to my son, <NpcName>Theo</>.
It’s exciting when you get a bite.//<portrait=normal>And some kinds of bait and certain lures will help you fish better.
Sometimes, you can waste a lot of time without getting much in return, though…//You have to be patient.
Fishing is a great skill to cultivate. It builds character and takes patience.
It’s exciting when you get a bite.//<portrait=normal>And some kinds of bait and certain lures will help you fish better.
Sometimes, you can waste a lot of time without getting much in return, though…//You have to be patient.
Nature is very giving. There’s plenty of food in the forest and around the lake.
Watch out for poisonous plants, though. Plenty of those, too.
I like cooking, especially if the ingredients are fresh from nature and not store-bought.
I do tai chi on my day off and spend the rest of the day scavenging around.
How’s your fishing skill, <PlayerName>$player</>?

I just try to live a quiet life, <PlayerName>$player</>.//I don’t want attention.
I think a lot of people who live here are the same way.

Attention can be dangerous. Look at Pufferfish Corporation.//I kept telling everybody, but nobody listened…//<portrait=concerned>We draw way too much notice with festivals and tourism. And now they want to drill here.
It’s not wise to show off too much beauty. It’s sad, it’s unfair… But so is life.
Fishing can be a way to spend quality time with friends and family. It can also improve your concentration.
Powerful stuff.
Even though I don’t fish for living anymore, I still like to read about fish. Found anything interesting lately?
The library has all kinds of informative books about fish, crops, and other stuff if you’re interested.

Back in the day, we had to jot down festivals and birthdays on the calendar ourselves. But now, you can just buy calendars preprinted from <NpcName>Dinda</> or get them from TV shopping.
Things are too easy for this generation. Everything seems to be online now. Is it a good thing or a bad thing? I don’t know.
I wouldn’t be too worried about being bad at fishing. It’s one of those things that improve with practice.
But a better fishing pole wouldn’t hurt if you’re trying to catch those feisty ones.
I fish after work when I don’t feel too tired. I suppose that’s the problem with being an old man. Even fun seems like hard work.
There are all kinds of different fish. Some of them are only out at night, so you need to keep the timing in mind if you’re looking for specific ones.
You can only make smoked salmon using salmon. I thought that was obvious, you know, given the name.
I fish after work when I don’t feel too tired. I suppose that’s the problem with being an old man. Even fun seems like hard work.
I’m never not tired. That’s not even a question anymore, just a matter of fact… No matter how much rest I get.
And at my age, <PlayerName>$player</>, there’s very little I can do about it.
I remain conflicted about not fixing up the shack. I know <NpcName>Sunny</> doesn’t want to do it. But we both know that the shack will need it one day.
In his defense, it’s where all his memories with...never mind.

Watch your step. I don’t want anybody to slip in my kitchen.
Watch your step. I don’t want anybody to slip in my kitchen.
The Cherry Blossom Festival is on the tenth. Jot it down on your calendar.
Oh, that’s true. Calendars nowadays already have festivals and birthdays on them.
The water is warm this time of year.
Its <NpcName>Sam</>’s birthday tomorrow. I think I’ll stop by in the morning to give him some of his favorite blueberry tarts.
Have you caught much salmon lately?
I still fish here and there, you know, especially now in salmon season.
I still fish here and there, you know, especially now in salmon season.
It’ll be another year before we can enjoy the Summer breeze… The Fall breeze isn’t the same.
I should collect more wood for smoking fish.
Yes, you do need wood to smoke fish.
At this time of year, we start keeping the heater on at night.
Watch your step, please. Slippery floor.
I don’t know how you youngsters do it, walking around in the snow and the cold.
I don’t know how you youngsters do it, walking around in the snow and the cold.
You’ll eventually find out who everyone really is if you give it some time. Some of them you’ll get along with and some you won’t, and that’s okay.
Because we’re different, <PlayerName>$player</>.
Oh, is it raining?//No wonder it’s colder than usual.
I guess I’m glad I’ll be spending my day next to a stove.

Ah yes. <PlayerName>$player</>.
Are you supposed to be back here?
If you want to talk, <NpcName>Sunny</> seems to be in the mood to chat.
Me? No. I’m not.

You can buy premade meals from <NpcName>Sam</> or <NpcName>Frank</> at the tavern.//<portrait=normal>He’s quite a cook and sells a lot of different home-cooked meals you can choose from… If you like stuff like that.
What do you need here, kid?
My knees hurt. I think I may have walked too fast.
If it isn’t your knees, it’s your hips. That’s old age for ya, <PlayerName>$player</>.
I want to have a relaxing day without bothering anybody… And vice versa.
But that seems like too much to ask nowadays.
*He’s doing his weekend stretches. Better leave him alone.*
I think this might be the best place to forage for mushrooms.//But I don’t know about the forest since I haven’t been there for a while.
Maybe the forest is a better place to gather mushrooms. I don’t know.
If you go to the beach, could you tell <NpcName>Theo</> not to sell his whole catch and bring some fish home?
Thanks.
My knees hurt. I think I may have walked too fast.
If it isn’t your knees, it’s your hips. That’s old age for ya, <PlayerName>$player</>.
I’m inclined to say that you’re lost, but I’m not sure.
Since you’re here, please excuse me while I get on with it.
I can’t help you much here. You’ll have to come see me at the Beach Shack if you need bait.
